# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: david-baltimore
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] The **1975 Nobel Prize in Literature** was awarded to the Italian poet Eugenio Montale (1896–1981) "for his distinctive poetry which, with great artistic sensitivity, has interpreted human values under the sign of an outlook on life with no illusions".
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] He is the fifth Italian laureate for the literature prize.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] Along with Giuseppe Ungaretti and Salvatore Quasimodo, Eugenio Montale is associated with the poetic school of hermeticsm, the Italian variant of the French symbolism movement, although Montale himself did not consider himself to be part of the hermetic school.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] When the Swedish Academy awarded him with the Nobel Prize in 1975, they called him “one of the most important poets of the contemporary West”.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] Montale was first nominated for the prize in 1955 by Nobel laureate T.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] It was followed in 1961 and from 1966 he became a regular nominee.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] By 1974, the Nobel committee had received 27 nominations in total before Montale was eventually awarded.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 1975, the Swedish Academy received nominations for 114 writers with 22 being from the Nobel Committee itself.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] The oldest nominee was Estonian poet Marie Under (aged 92) and the youngest was the Irish poet Brendan Kennelly (aged 39).
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] The authors Peter Anson, Hannah Arendt, Mikhail Bakhtin, Kersti Bergroth, Arthur Herbert Dodd, Julian Huxley, Edward Hyams, Murray Leinster, Constance Malleson, Thomas H.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] Parry-Williams, Kate Seredy, Robert Cedric Sherriff, Sydney Goodsir Smith, Ivan Sokolov-Mikitov, Elizabeth Taylor and P.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] Wodehouse died in 1975 without having been nominated for the prize.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] The members of the Nobel committee variously proposed Graham Greene, Saul Bellow (awarded in 1976), Doris Lessing (awarded in 2007) and Nadine Gordimer (awarded in 1991) as the recipients of the 1975 Nobel Prize in Literature, but struggled to agree on one candidate.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] A speech by Academy member and former Nobel committee member Henry Olsson on 25 September appears to have convinced the members of the Swedish Academy to agree on awarding the fifth shortlisted candidate, Eugenio Montale.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] As none of the committee members had placed him as their first proposal, Montale is said being a compromise second choice by the Swedish Academy.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] In Italy, the awarding of the Nobel Prize to Montale was positively received.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] Eugenio Montale delivered his Nobel lecture on 12 December 1975.
[src:david-baltimore/1975-nobel-prize-in-literature] Entitled "Is Poetry Still Possible?", he spoke about the art of poetry and poetry's place in the modern world of mass communication.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p01] The following is a partial list of minor planets, running from minor-planet number 73001 through 74000, inclusive.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p01] The primary data for this and other partial lists is based on JPL's "Small-Body Orbital Elements" and data available from the Minor Planet Center.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p01] Critical list information is also provided by the MPC, unless otherwise specified from Lowell Observatory.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p01] A detailed description of the table's columns and additional sources are given on the main page including a complete list of every page in this series, and a statistical break-up on the dynamical classification of minor planets.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p01] Also see the summary list of all named bodies in numerical and alphabetical order, and the corresponding naming citations for the number range of this particular list.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p01] New namings may only be added to this list after official publication, as the preannouncement of names is condemned by the Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:david-baltimore/73079-davidbaltimore-p02] J. van Houten, I. van Houten-Groeneveld, T.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Previously at the University of California, Berkeley, he served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] His academic research focuses on nanomaterials, particularly nanocrystal fabrication for biomedical and renewable energy applications.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Paul Alivisatos was born in Chicago, Illinois, where he lived until the age of 10, when his family moved to Athens, Greece.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He returned to the United States to attend the University of Chicago in the late 1970s.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos received a Bachelor of Arts degree (with honors) with a major in chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1981 and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1986.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral advisor at Berkeley was Charles B.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral thesis was titled *The photophysical properties of molecules near metal and semiconductor surfaces*.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] After receiving his doctorate, Alivisatos joined AT&T Bell Labs working with Louis E.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Brus, and began research in the field of nanotechnology.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos returned to the University of California, Berkeley in 1988 as an assistant professor of chemistry.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He was promoted to associate professor in 1993 and to full professor in 1995.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In administrative roles, Alivisatos served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as the university's interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In August 2013, he was appointed as Samsung Distinguished Professor in Nanoscience and Nanotechnology Research.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He was also the founding director of the Kavli Energy Nanosciences Institute (ENSI).
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos joined the Materials Sciences Division at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in 1991.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He served as associate laboratory director for physical sciences from 2005 to 2007.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In 2008, he became deputy director, and he stepped in as interim director after Steven Chu left to become United States Secretary of Energy under the first Obama administration.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] On November 19, 2009, Alivisatos was appointed 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He refocused the lab on renewable energy and climate research, oversaw new facilities, deepened ties to the national innovation ecosystem, and advanced collaborations that sped technology transfer across industries from autos to medicine.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] On March 23, 2015, he announced that he would step down from the directorship once a successor was named.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] On February 26, 2021, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago named Alivisatos as the incoming 14th president of the University of Chicago, with his term beginning on September 1, 2021.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He succeeded Robert Zimmer, who served as the university president from July 2006 to August 2021.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to the office of the president, he was named the John D.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] MacArthur Distinguished Service Professor, chair of the Board of Governors of Argonne National Laboratory, and chair of the Board of Directors of Fermi Forward Discovery Group LLC, which operates the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] On September 24, 2025, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago extended Alivisatos's presidency through June 2030.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is an internationally recognized authority on nano chemistry in the synthesis of semiconductor quantum dots and multi-shaped artificial nanostructures.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Further, he is a world expert on the chemistry of nanoscale crystals; one of his papers (Science, 271: 933–937, 1996) has been cited over 13,800 times.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He is also an expert on how these can be applied, for example as biological markers (e.g., Science, 281: 2013–16, 1998; a paper cited over 10,900 times).
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition, his use of DNA in this area (DNA nanotechnology) has shown the surprising versatility of this molecule.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He has used it to direct crystal growth and create new materials, as in Nature, 382: 609–11, 1996, and even to measure nanoscale distances (see Nature Nanotechnology, 1: 47–52, 2006).
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In February 2011, Alivisatos was ranked fifth among the world's top 100 chemists for the period 2000–2010 in the list released by Thomson Reuters.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He is widely recognized as being the first to demonstrate that semiconductor nanocrystals can be grown into complex two-dimensional shapes, as opposed to simple one-dimensional spheres.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos proved that controlling the growth of nanocrystals is the key to controlling both their size and shape.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] This achievement altered the nanoscience landscape and paved the way for a slew of new potential applications, including biomedical diagnostics, revolutionary photovoltaic cells, and LED materials.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Given that a nanocrystal is virtually all surface and no interior, its properties can vary considerably as the crystal grows in size.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Prior to Alivisatos's research, all non-metal nanocrystals were dot-shaped, meaning they were essentially one-dimensional.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] No techniques had been reported for making two-dimensional or rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals that would also be of uniform size.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] However, in a landmark paper that appeared in the March 2, 2000, issue of the journal Nature, Alivisatos reported on techniques used to select the size but vary the shapes of the nanocrystals produced.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] This was hailed as a major breakthrough in nanocrystal fabrication because rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals can be stacked to create nano-sized electronic devices.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos went on to use his techniques to create an entirely new generation of hybrid solar cells that combined nanotechnology with plastic electronics.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding scientist of Quantum Dot Corporation, a company that makes crystalline nanoscale tags that are used in the study of cell behavior.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] (Quantum Dot is now part of Life Technologies.) He also founded the nanotechnology company Nanosys, and Solexant, a photovoltaic start-up that has since restarted as Siva Power.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding editor of *Nano Letters*, a publication of the American Chemical Society.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He formerly served on the Senior Editorial Board of *Science*.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He has also served on the editorial advisory boards of*ACS Nano*, the *Journal of Physical Chemistry*, *Chemical Physics*, the *Journal of Chemical Physics*, and *Advanced Materials*.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to those listed above, Alivisatos has held fellowships with the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the American Physical Society (1996), and the American Chemical Society.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] He is a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:david-baltimore/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is married to Nicole Alivisatos, a retired chemist, former editor of the journal Nano Letters, and daughter of the noted chemist, Gábor A.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Starting from Rainwater's concept of an irregular-shaped liquid drop model of the nucleus, Bohr and Mottelson developed a detailed theory that was in close agreement with experiments.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Since his father, Niels Bohr, had won the prize in 1922, he and his father are one of the several pairs of fathers and sons who have both won the Nobel Prize.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr was born in Copenhagen on 19 June 1922, the fourth of six sons of the physicist Niels Bohr and his wife Margrethe Bohr (née Nørlund).
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] His oldest brother, Christian, died in a boating accident in 1934, and his youngest, Harald, was severely disabled and placed away from the home in Copenhagen at the age of four.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He would later die from childhood meningitis.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Of the others, Hans became a physician; Erik, a chemical engineer; and Ernest, a lawyer and Olympic athlete who played field hockey for Denmark at the 1948 Summer Olympics in London.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The family lived at the Institute of Theoretical Physics at the University of Copenhagen, now known as the Niels Bohr Institute, where he grew up surrounded by physicists who were working with his father, such as Hans Kramers, Oskar Klein, Yoshio Nishina, Wolfgang Pauli and Werner Heisenberg.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In 1932, the family moved to the Carlsberg Æresbolig, a mansion donated by Carl Jacobsen, the heir to Carlsberg breweries, to be used as an honorary residence by the Dane who had made the most prominent contribution to science, literature, or the arts.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr went to high school at Sortedam Gymnasium in Copenhagen.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In 1940, shortly after the German occupation of Denmark in April, he entered the University of Copenhagen, where he studied physics.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He assisted his father, helping draft correspondence and articles related to epistemology and physics.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In September 1943, word reached his family that the Nazis considered them to be Jewish, because Bohr's grandmother, Ellen Adler Bohr, had been Jewish, and that they therefore were in danger of being arrested.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The Danish resistance helped the family escape by sea to Sweden.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr arrived there in October 1943, and then flew to Britain on a de Havilland Mosquito operated by British Overseas Airways Corporation.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The Mosquitoes were unarmed high-speed bomber aircraft that had been converted to carry small, valuable cargoes or important passengers.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] By flying at high speed and high altitude, they could cross German-occupied Norway, and yet avoid German fighters.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr, equipped with a parachute, flying suit, and oxygen mask, spent the three-hour flight lying on a mattress in the aircraft's bomb bay.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] On arrival in London, Bohr rejoined his father, who had flown to Britain the week before.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He officially became a junior researcher at the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, but actually served as personal assistant and secretary to his father.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The two worked on Tube Alloys, the British atomic bomb project.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] On 30 December 1943, they made the first of a number of visits to the United States, where his father was a consultant to the Manhattan Project.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Due to his father's fame, they were given false names; Bohr became James Baker, and his father, Nicholas Baker.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In 1945, the director of the Los Alamos Laboratory, J.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Robert Oppenheimer, asked them to review the design of the modulated neutron initiator.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] That they had reached this conclusion put Enrico Fermi's concerns about the viability of the design to rest.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The initiators performed flawlessly in the bombs used in the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August 1945.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In August 1945, with the war ended, Bohr returned to Denmark, where he resumed his university education, graduating with a master's degree in 1946, with a thesis concerned with some aspects of atomic stopping power problems.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In early 1948, Bohr became a member of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] While paying a visit to Columbia University, he met Isidor Isaac Rabi, who sparked in him an interest in recent discoveries related to the hyperfine structure of deuterium.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] This led to Bohr becoming a visiting fellow at Columbia from January 1949 to August 1950.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] While in the United States, Bohr married Marietta Soffer on 11 March 1950.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] They had three children: Vilhelm, Tomas and Margrethe.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] By the late 1940s it was known that the properties of atomic nuclei could not be explained by then-current models such as the liquid drop model developed by Niels Bohr amongst others.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The shell model, developed in 1949 by Maria Goeppert Mayer and others, allowed some additional features to be explained, in particular the so-called magic numbers.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] However, there were also properties that could not be explained, including the non-spherical distribution of charge in certain nuclei.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In a 1950 paper, James Rainwater of Columbia University suggested a variant of the drop model of the nucleus that could explain a non-spherical charge distribution.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Rainwater's model postulated a nucleus like a balloon with balls inside that distort the surface as they move about.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He discussed the idea with Bohr, who was visiting Columbia at the time, and had independently conceived the same idea, and had, about a month after Rainwater's submission, submitted for publication a paper that discussed the same problem, but along more general lines.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr imagined a rotating, irregular-shaped nucleus with a form of surface tension.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr developed the idea further, in 1951 publishing a paper that comprehensively treated the relationship between oscillations of the surface of the nucleus and the movement of the individual nucleons.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Upon his return to Copenhagen in 1950, Bohr began working with Ben Roy Mottelson to compare the theoretical work with experimental data.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In three papers, that were published in 1952 and 1953, Bohr and Mottelson demonstrated close agreement between theory and experiment; for example, showing that the energy levels of certain nuclei could be described by a rotation spectrum.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] They were thereby able to reconcile the shell model with Rainwater's concept.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] This work stimulated many new theoretical and experimental studies.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr, Mottelson and Rainwater were jointly awarded the 1975 Nobel Prize in Physics "for the discovery of the connection between collective motion and particle motion in atomic nuclei and the development of the theory of the structure of the atomic nucleus based on this connection".
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Because his father had been awarded the prize in 1922, Bohr became one of only four pairs of fathers and sons to win the Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Only after doing his Nobel Prize-winning research did Bohr receive his doctorate from the University of Copenhagen, in 1954, writing his thesis on "Rotational States of Atomic Nuclei".
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr became a professor at the University of Copenhagen in 1956, and, following his father's death in 1962, succeeded him as director of the Niels Bohr Institute, a position he held until 1970.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He remained active there until he retired in 1992.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He was also a member of the board of the Nordic Institute for Theoretical Physics from its inception in 1957, and was its director from 1975 to 1981.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In addition to the Nobel Prize, he won the Dannie Heineman Prize for Mathematical Physics in 1960, the Atoms for Peace Award in 1969, H.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] C. Ørsted Medal in 1970, Rutherford Medal and Prize in 1972, John Price Wetherill Medal in 1974, and the Ole Rømer medal in 1976.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr and Mottelson continued to work together, publishing a two-volume monograph, *Nuclear Structure*.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] The first volume, *Single-Particle Motion,* appeared in 1969; the second, *Nuclear Deformations,* in 1975.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In 1972 Bohr was awarded an honorary degree, doctor philos. honoris causa, at the Norwegian Institute of Technology, later part of Norwegian University of Science and Technology.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He was a member of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters from 1980.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr was also an elected member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the American Philosophical Society, and the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] In 1981, Bohr became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] His son, Tomas Bohr, is a professor of physics at the Technical University of Denmark, working in the area of fluid dynamics.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Aage Bohr died in Copenhagen on 8 September 2009.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] He was survived by his second wife and children.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] Bohr's Nobel Prize medal was sold at auction in November 2011.
[src:david-baltimore/aage-bohr] It was subsequently sold at auction in April 2019 for $90,000.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Abel Wolman was born to Louis and Rose Wachsman Wolman on June 10, 1892 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] He was the fourth eldest child of Polish-Jewish immigrants.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Wolman received his high school education from the Baltimore City College in 1909.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Following his high school education, Wolman received his Bachelor of Arts in 1913 as a pre-med major.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Although Wolman was interested in becoming a doctor, his mother's insistence on studying engineering led him to pursue a degree in engineering.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] He then went on to complete a Bachelor of Science in Engineering at the Johns Hopkins University, graduating in 1915 as the fourth person to receive a degree at the newly-established Whiting School of Engineering.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Although Wolman did not complete a doctorate degree, his work in the field of sanitary engineering led to him being awarded an honorary Doctor of Engineering in 1937.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Wolman was also awarded a Doctor of Humane Letters from the Maryland Institute College of Arts and a Doctor of Law by the Johns Hopkins University in 1969.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Wolman served an extensive career in sanitary engineering, working in both environmental and public health services as well as in academics.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1914, he started his long career in public health as an assistant engineer working for the United States Public Health Service.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1922, Wolman became the Chief Engineer of the Maryland State Department of Health, where he served for 18 years until 1939.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] While working in the public health sector, Wolman conducted research related to sanitation and public health.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] He is best known for his 1919 contribution, with chemist Linn Enslow, in the standardization of chlorinating Baltimore's drinking-water supply.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] His efforts there helped develop the plan for Baltimore's water supply so thoroughly and effectively that it remains well-provided for growth through the 21st century.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] His work also benefited water systems in New York, Detroit and Columbus, Ohio.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] At that same time, he served as the Department of Sanitary Engineering's chairman until his official retirement in 1962.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] During his time as a sanitary engineering lecturer, he was asked to lecture at many prestigious universities, including Harvard University, Princeton University, University of Southern California, and University of Chicago.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] He was appointed Professor Emeritus in 1962, but had no desire to retire from professional life, so he continued his teaching and research in addition to serving as a consultant to the many governments and municipalities that requested his advice and assistance.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Supplementing his professional life, Wolman also held many important positions in the committees of professional societies and journal publications.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1916, he joined the American Public Health Association as an associate editor of the organization's monthly publication, *American Journal of Public Health,* where he eventually became the editor in 1955 until 1957.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Within the American Public Health Association, Wolman served as Chairman of the Public Health Engineering Section and Chairman of the Committee on Research and Standards.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Through their marriage, Wolman had one son, named Markley (M.) Gordon Wolman.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Maintaining a lively and witty personality, Wolman was favorable amongst many of the students he interacted with as a professor.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] From colleagues and family members that knew Wolman well, he has been described as being very well-organized and always perceptive towards his problems and analyses related to work.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Wolman died at his home in Baltimore, Maryland on February 22, 1989, aged 96 years old.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In collaboration with Linn Enslow, Wolman wanted to standardize a chlorination method to purify municipal water supplies.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] At the time, the purification of water with chlorine was known and employed in cities, but the problem that Wolman and Enslow highlighted in this publication was that the dosage of chlorine used by cities were unreliable and unscientific.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] As a result, municipal water supplies were often incorrectly purified, leading to failures in performance marked by diseases.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Wolman and Enslow began their experiment by describing their observations on the rate of chlorine absorption in different water samples that varied in bacteria, color, turbidity, oxidizable compounds, and other purity factors.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In "The Metabolism of Cities", Wolman highlighted three major "metabolic" problems that plagued major cities in the United States and offered his insight on the reality of those problems and possible solutions.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] He defined the metabolic requirements of a city as all materials and commodities needed to sustain its population, including all processes related to the proper removal and disposal of waste products produced in daily life.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] However, he pointed out that many major US cities share three metabolic problems: (1) lack of an adequate water supply, (2) ineffective disposal of sewage, and (3) poor control of air pollution.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Throughout most of the paper, Wolman provided relevant statistics and figures to underscore the proposed metabolic problems and analyzed historical municipal proposals designed to alleviate those metabolic problems.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] He concluded the article on a somewhat optimistic note, mentioning that the future of water sanitation, sewage disposal, and eliminating air pollutants is hopeful.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] However, in order to reach that future, Wolman called for immediate action and planning of policies and programs needed to combat the three metabolic problems.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Since the publication of this paper, there have been many studies performed to develop viable solutions to tackle the water shortages, waste disposal, and air pollution issues proposed by Wolman.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] For example, in 1999, civil and environmental engineers at the University of California, Berkeley published a research paper that confirmed the presence of water shortages in the United States and advocated for cities to take water recycling and reuse measures.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] For his efforts in public health practices and engineering skills on a local and global level, Wolman was granted multiple awards.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1948, Wolman was awarded the Sedgwick Memorial Medal by the American Public Health Association for his contributions in the field of public health.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1960, he was awarded the Albert Lasker Special Award in Public Health, which is an award "for outstanding contributions in research related to diseases which are the main causes of death and disability and for distinguished service in the field of public health administration.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1967, Wolman was awarded the William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement for his contributions in the field of science.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1968, Wolman was awarded the first Lewis L.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1973, Wolman was awarded the Milton Stover Eisenhower Medal.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1974, Wolman was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1976, Wolman was awarded the Tyler Prize for Environmental Achievement and the Ben Gurion Award.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Both in 1973 and 1977, Wolman was awarded the American Water Works Association Award.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1986, Wolman was awarded the Robert E.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Horton Medal and the John Wesley Powell Award.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Finally, in 1999, The Baltimore Sun named Wolman "Marylander of the Century".
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] Following the death of Wolman, multiple tributes were created in his honor.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] For individuals that work in the water industry, the American Water Works Association annually presents the Abel Wolman Award of Excellence since 1985.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In May 1966, the Johns Hopkins University named a newly acquired dormitory Wolman Hall, which continues to house first year students.
[src:david-baltimore/abel-wolman] In 1986, the City of Baltimore renamed its public works building to the Abel Wolman Municipal Building, honoring his years of service to the city.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] The **Abelson murine leukemia virus** (**Ab-MLV** or **A-MuLV**) is a retrovirus (Class VI) used to induce malignant transformation of murine lymphoid cells.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] As a retrovirus, it has a single-stranded, positive sense RNA genome which replicates via a DNA intermediate mediated by a reverse transcriptase.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] The Abelson murine leukemia virus is named for the American pediatrician Herbert T.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] Abelson, who together with Louise S Rabstein, first described and isolated it.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] A-MuLV causes a rapidly progressive lymphosarcoma known as Abelson disease in mice, which is a type of leukemia that does not involve the thymus.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] However, this is only possible when the host cell is co-infected with a helper virus which provides functions it needs to be able to replicate which it does not code for in its own genome such as a reverse transcriptase and some major structural proteins.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] As such, A-MuLV can be described as a dependovirus.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] A highly efficient helper virus commonly used when growing A-MuLV *in vitro* is Moloney murine leukemia virus (M-MuLV).
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] It causes leukemia directly by interfering with the normal growth and differentiation processes of lymphocytes.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] It can infect B-cells which was shown by the fact that some tumor cells can be seen to have immunoglobulins (Ig) on their surface although most tumor cells do not have characteristic receptors on their surface indicating that they are undifferentiated cells.
[src:david-baltimore/abelson-murine-leukemia-virus] *In vitro* studies have shown that lymphocyte infection produces tumor cell populations comprising three types of cells: stable productive cells, non-productive cells and cells which produced defective virus particles which are not infective.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The **American Academy of Achievement** (colloquially known as the **Academy of Achievement**) is a nonprofit corporation that recognizes high-achieving people in diverse fields and gives them the opportunity to meet one another.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The academy also brings together leaders with promising graduate students for mentorship.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] It hosts an International Achievement Summit, which ends with an awards ceremony during which new members are inducted.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Founded in 1961 by *Sports Illustrated* and *LIFE* magazine photographer Brian Reynolds, the American Academy of Achievement recognizes high achievers in public service, business, science and exploration, sports, and the arts.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Reynolds established the academy after realizing that the famous people he photographed from different fields did not usually get to meet one another.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] A 1989 *San Francisco Chronicle* article called the organization "little-publicized but immensely powerful".
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] According to William DeVries, who helped develop the first artificial heart, "It is a social network.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Now I can call Chuck Yeager up, or Philip 'Bo' Knight, and they'll return my calls, ask me out places.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] I promised myself I would never ask the people here for money, but I know a lot of scientists who do." Reynolds also wanted to bring together highly accomplished leaders with promising students, to inspire them.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] At the 1990 summit in Chicago, for example, student delegates "rubbed shoulders" with Ronald Reagan, Maya Angelou and Michael Jordan, and in 1995, students met with inductees including George H.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Bush, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Lady Bird Johnson, Robin Williams, Mike Krzyzewski and Rosa Parks.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Academy members and summit attendees have also included Jimmy Carter, Colin Powell, Maya Lin, Barbra Streisand, Mikhail Gorbachev, Steven Spielberg, and George Lucas.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] In 1985, Reynolds's son, Wayne Reynolds, took over the leadership, becoming the executive director of the academy.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] In 1999, he was selected as the board chairman.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] In the 1990s, Reynolds moved the organization's headquarters from Malibu, California, to Washington, D.C.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Reynolds Foundation donated $9 million to the academy.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The annual summit is attended by graduate students and young innovators from the U.S. and overseas, like Sergey Brin and Larry Page, computer science graduate students who later founded Google.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The summits were originally attended by high school students chosen for their academic achievement and extracurricular activities.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Preceding the awards dinner are three days of panels, presentations and informal dialogues between the students and inductees.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Many inductees return multiple years to participate in the panels, programming and networking.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] On September 9, 1961, the academy hosted its first International Achievement Summit.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Held in Monterey, California, it included a "Banquet of the Golden Plate" award ceremony, named for the gold-plate service used for special occasions by the Palace Hotel in San Francisco, which provided the service for the ceremony.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Physicist Edward Teller was the keynote speaker, and warned of the United States' poor performance in the atomic arms race.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Awardees at the inaugural ceremony included engineers Charles Stark Draper and Kelly Johnson, General Douglas MacArthur and film director William Wyler.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Other attendees included Nobel laureate Willard Libby (Chemistry, 1960) and future Nobel laureate Luis Walter Alvarez (Physics, 1968).
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The first honorees were chosen by a national board of governors, but subsequent honorees have been selected by the Golden Plate Awards Council, which consists of academy awardees.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] At the 13th annual summit, held in June 1974 in Salt Lake City, Academy member Leon Jaworski, the Special Prosecutor overseeing the Watergate investigations at the time, said in his keynote address that he expected to win a Supreme Court case to get subpoenaed tapes from President Richard Nixon.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Among the awardees at the summit were actor James Stewart, professional athlete John Havlicek, and Nobel Laureate chemist Paul Flory.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The 25th annual American Academy of Achievement Summit took place in 1986 in Washington, D.C.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The ceremony was addressed by former inductees Chuck Yeager and Erma Bombeck, and was attended by a group of 390 high school graduates assembled from across the U.S.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] New members admitted to the academy at the event included boxer Muhammad Ali, filmmaker Steven Spielberg, Nobel Prize laureate Isidor Isaac Rabi, opera singer Leontyne Price, and country singer Loretta Lynn, the first country music artist ever admitted into the academy.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The 2002 summit was held in Dublin, and was hosted by then-Taoiseach (prime minister) and inductee Bertie Ahern.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Former President Bill Clinton held private talks during the summit with Irish nationalist politician John Hume that reportedly concerned the conflict in Northern Ireland as well as other international conflicts.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] New inductees into the academy in 2002 included Clinton, U2 lead singer Bono, and Afghan president Hamid Karzai.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The 50th-anniversary American Academy of Achievement Summit was held in Washington D.C., in October 2012, and was attended by delegates from 29 countries.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The five-day event included a dinner at the Supreme Court of the United States, which four of the justices attended.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Newly inducted academy members who spoke at the meeting included then-United States Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta and Nobel laureates Roger Tsien and Adam Riess.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] In 2012, Ray Dalio received the Golden Plate Award of the American Academy of Achievement presented by Carlyle Group co-founder David Rubenstein, during the International Achievement Summit in Washington, D.C.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] The 2021 awards ceremony took place in Los Angeles on December 23.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Among the awardees was Katalin Karikó, a biochemist whose research with Drew Weissman underpins the mRNA COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Other awardees honored at the summit include Kenyan track and field athletes Faith Kipyegon and Beatrice Chebet, who both won gold medals at the 2024 Summer Olympics in Paris.
[src:david-baltimore/academy-of-achievement] Both received their Golden Plate awards from Kenyan President William Ruto.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] At age 37, Baltimore won the Nobel Prize with Renato Dulbecco and Howard M.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Temin "for their discoveries concerning the interaction between tumour viruses and the genetic material of the cell", specifically the discovery of the enzyme reverse transcriptase.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He contributed to immunology, virology, cancer research, biotechnology, and recombinant DNA research.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He also trained many doctoral students and postdoctoral fellows, several of whom have gone on to notable and distinguished research careers.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In addition to the Nobel Prize, he received a number of other awards, including the U.S.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] National Medal of Science in 1999 and the Lasker Award in 2021.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore was born on March 7, 1938, in Manhattan, New York, to Gertrude (Lipschitz) and Richard Baltimore.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Raised in the Queens neighborhoods of Forest Hills and Rego Park, he moved with his family to suburban Great Neck, New York, while he was in second grade because his mother felt that the city schools were inadequate.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] His father had been raised as an Orthodox Jew and his mother was an atheist, and Baltimore observed Jewish holidays and would attend synagogue with his father through his Bar Mitzvah.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He graduated from Great Neck North High School in 1956, and credits his interest in biology to a high-school summer spent at the Jackson Laboratory's Summer Student Program in Bar Harbor, Maine.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] It was at this program that he met Howard Temin, with whom he would later share the Nobel Prize.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore earned his bachelor's degree in chemistry with high honors at Swarthmore College in 1960.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was introduced to molecular biology by George Streisinger, under whose mentorship he worked for a summer at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory as part of the inaugural cohort of the Undergraduate Research Program in 1959.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] There he also met two new MIT faculty, future Nobel Laureate Salvador Luria and Cyrus Levinthal, who were scouting for candidates for a new program of graduate education in molecular biology.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Luria and Levinthal invited Baltimore to apply to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore's future promise was evident in his work as a graduate student when he entered MIT's graduate program in biology in 1960.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] His early interest in phage genetics quickly yielded to a passion for animal viruses.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He took the Cold Spring Harbor course on animal virology in 1961 and chose to move to Richard Franklin's lab at Rockefeller University to complete his PhD research on animal virology.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] There he made fundamental discoveries on virus replication and its effect on cell metabolism, including the first description of an RNA replicase, finishing his PhD in only two years.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] After his PhD, Baltimore returned to MIT for postdoctoral research with James E.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He continued his work on virus replication using poliovirus and pursued training in enzymology with Jerard Hurwitz at Albert Einstein College of Medicine in 1964.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In February 1965, Baltimore was recruited by Renato Dulbecco to the newly established Salk Institute for Biological Studies in La Jolla as an independent research associate.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] There he investigated poliovirus RNA replication and began a long and storied career of mentoring other scientists' early careers including Marc Girard, and Michael Jacobson.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] They discovered the mechanism of proteolytic cleavage of viral polyprotein precursors, pointing to the importance of proteolytic processing in the synthesis of eukaryotic proteins.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He also met his future wife, Alice Huang, who began working with Baltimore at Salk in 1967.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He and Alice together carried out key experiments on defective interfering particles and viral pseudo types.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] During this work, he made a key discovery that polio produced its viral proteins as a single large polyprotein that was subsequently processed into individual functional peptides.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1968, he was recruited once more by soon-to-be Nobel laureate Salvador Luria to the department of biology at MIT as an associate professor of microbiology.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Huang also moved to MIT to continue her research on vesicular stomatitis virus (VSV).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] They became a couple, and married in October 1968.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] At MIT, Huang, Baltimore, and graduate student Martha Stampfer discovered that VSV replication involved an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase within the virus particle, and used a novel strategy to replicate its RNA genome.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] VSV entered a host cell as a single negative strand of RNA, but brought with it RNA polymerase to stimulate the processes of transcription and replication of more RNA.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore extended this work and examined two RNA tumor viruses, Rauscher murine leukemia virus and Rous sarcoma virus.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He went on to discover reverse transcriptase (RTase or RT) – the enzyme that polymerizes DNA from an RNA template.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In doing so, he discovered a distinct class of viruses, later called retroviruses, that use an RNA template to catalyze synthesis of viral DNA.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This overturned the simplified version of the central dogma of molecular biology that stated that genetic information flows unidirectionally from DNA to RNA to proteins.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Reverse transcriptase is essential for the reproduction of retroviruses, allowing such viruses to turn viral RNA strands into viral DNA strands.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The viruses that fall into this category include HIV.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The discovery of reverse transcriptase, made contemporaneously with Howard Temin, who had proposed the provirus hypothesis, showed that genetic information could traffic bidirectionally between DNA and RNA.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] They published these findings in back-to-back papers in the journal *Nature*.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This discovery made it easier to isolate and reproduce individual genes, and was heralded as evidence that molecular and virological approaches to understanding cancer would yield new cancer treatments.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This may have influenced President Richard Nixon's war on cancer, which was launched in 1971 and substantially increased research funding for the disease.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1972, at the age of 34, Baltimore was awarded tenure as a professor of biology at MIT, a post that he held until 1997.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore also helped Paul Berg and Maxine Singer to organize the Asilomar Conference on Recombinant DNA, held in February 1975.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1973, he was awarded an American Cancer Society Professor of Microbiology that provided substantial salary support.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Also in 1973, he became one of the early faculty members in the newly organized MIT Center for Cancer Research (CCR), capping a creative and industrious period of his career with nearly fifty research publications including the paradigm-shifting paper on reverse transcriptase.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Luria and quickly achieved pre-eminence with a group of faculty including Baltimore, Phillips Robbins, Herman Eisen, Philip Sharp, and Robert Weinberg.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore was honored as a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1974.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He returned to New York City in 1975, for a year-long sabbatical at Rockefeller University working again with Jim Darnell.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1975, at the age of 37, he shared the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine with Howard Temin and Renato Dulbecco.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] After winning the Nobel Prize, Baltimore reorganized his laboratory, refocusing on immunology and virology, with immunoglobulin gene expression as a major area of interest.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He tackled new problems such as the pathogenesis of Abelson murine leukemia virus (AMuLV), lymphocyte differentiation and related topic in immunology.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1980, his group isolated the oncogene in AMuLV and showed it was a member of a new class of protein kinases that used the amino acid tyrosine as a phosphoacceptor.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This type of enzymatic activity was also discovered by Tony Hunter, who has done extensive work in the area.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He also continued to pursue fundamental questions in RNA viruses and in 1981, Baltimore and Vincent Racaniello, a post-doctoral fellow in his laboratory, used recombinant DNA technology to generate a plasmid encoding the genome of poliovirus, an animal RNA virus.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The plasmid DNA was introduced into cultured mammalian cells and infectious poliovirus was produced.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The infectious clone, DNA encoding the genome of a virus, is a standard tool used today in virology.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1982, with a charitable donation by businessman and philanthropist Edwin C.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] "Jack" Whitehead, Baltimore was asked to help establish a self-governed research institute dedicated to basic biomedical research.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore persuaded Whitehead that MIT would be the ideal home for the new institute, convinced that it would be superior at hiring the best researchers in biology at the time, thus ensuring quality.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Persuading MIT faculty to support the idea was far more difficult.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] MIT as an institution had never housed another before, and concerns were raised that the wealth of the institute might skew the biology department in directions faculty did not wish to take, and that Baltimore himself would gain undue influence over hiring within the department.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The controversy was made worse by an article published by the Boston Globe framing the institute as corporate takeover of MIT.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] After a year of intensive discussions and planning, faculty finally voted in favor of the institute.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Whitehead, Baltimore, and the rest of the planning team devised a unique structure of an independent research institute composed of "members" with a close relationship with the department of biology of MIT.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This structure continues to this day to attract an elite interactive group of faculty to the Department of Biology at MIT and has served as a model for other distinguished institutes such as the Broad Institute.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The Whitehead Institute for Biomedical Research (WIBR) was launched with $35 million to construct and equip a new building located across the street from the MIT cancer center at 9 Cambridge Center in Cambridge Massachusetts.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The institute also received $5 million per year in guaranteed income and a substantial endowment in his will (for a total gift of $135 million).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Whitehead Institute's contributions to bioscience have long been consistently outstanding.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The Whitehead Institute was an important partner in the Human Genome Project.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore served as director of the WIBR and expanded the faculty and research areas into key areas of research including mouse and drosophila genetics.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] During this time, Baltimore's own research program thrived in the new Institute.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Important breakthroughs from Baltimore's lab include the discovery of the key transcription factor NF-κB by Dr.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This was part of a broader investigation to identify nuclear factors required for lg gene expression in B lymphocytes.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] However, NF-κB turned out to have much broader importance in both innate and adaptive immunity and viral regulation.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] NF-κB is involved in regulating cellular responses and belongs to the category of "rapid-acting" primary transcription factors.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] As early as 1984, Rudolf Grosschedl and David Weaver, postdoctoral fellows, in Baltimore's laboratory, were experimenting with the creation of transgenic mice as a model for the study of disease.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] They suggested that "control of lg gene rearrangement might be the only mechanism that determines the specificity of heavy chain gene expression within the lymphoid cell lineage." in 1987, they created transgenic mice with the fused gene that developed fatal leukemia.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1990, as a student in David Baltimore's laboratory at MIT, George Q.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Daley demonstrated that a fusion protein called bcr-abl is sufficient to stimulate cell growth and cause chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This work helped to identify a class of proteins that become hyperactive in specific types of cancer cells.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] It helped to lay the groundwork for a new type of drug, attacking cancer at the genetic level: Brian Druker's development of the anti-cancer drug Imatinib (Gleevec), which deactivates bcr-abl proteins.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Gleevec has shown impressive results in treating chronic myelogenous leukemia and also promise in treating gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore served as the director of the Whitehead Institute until July 1, 1990, when he was appointed the sixth president of Rockefeller University in New York City.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He moved his research group to New York in stages and continued to make creative contributions to virology and cellular regulation.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He also began important reforms in fiscal and faculty management and promoted the status of junior faculty at the university.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] After resigning on December 3, 1991 (see Imanishi-Kari case), Baltimore remained on the Rockefeller University faculty and continued research until the spring of 1994.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was invited to return to MIT and rejoined the faculty as the Ivan R.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Cottrell Professor of Molecular Biology and Immunology.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] On May 13, 1997, Baltimore was appointed president of the California Institute of Technology (Caltech).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He began serving in the office October 15, 1997 and was inaugurated March 9, 1998.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] During Baltimore's tenure at Caltech, United States president Bill Clinton awarded Baltimore the National Medal of Science in 1999 for his numerous contributions to the scientific world.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2004, Rockefeller University gave Baltimore its highest honor, a Doctor of Science degree (*honoris causa*).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2003, as a postdoctoral fellow in Baltimore's lab at Caltech, Matthew Porteus was the first to demonstrate precise gene editing in human cells using chimeric nucleases.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In October 2005, Baltimore resigned the office of the president of Caltech, saying, "This is not a decision that I have made easily, but I am convinced that the interests of the Institute will be best served by a presidential transition at this particular time in its history ...".
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Former Georgia Tech Provost Jean-Lou Chameau succeeded Baltimore as president of Caltech.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore was appointed president emeritus and the Robert Andrews Milikan Professor of Biology at Caltech and remained an active member of the institute's community.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] On January 21, 2021, Caltech president Thomas F.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Rosenbaum announced the removal of the name of Caltech's founding president and first Nobel laureate, Robert A.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Millikan, from campus buildings, assets, and honors due to Millikan's substantial participation in the eugenics movement.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore's title was changed to "Distinguished Professor of Biology".
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore's laboratory at Caltech focused on two major research areas: understanding the development and functioning of the mammalian immune system and translational studies creating viral vectors to make the immune system more effective in resisting cancer.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Their basic studies went in two directions: understanding the diverse activity of the NF-κB transcription factor, and understanding the normal and pathologic functions of microRNA.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] A primary focus of Baltimore's lab was use of gene therapy methods to treat HIV and cancer.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In the early 2000s one of Baltimore's graduate students, Lili Yang, developed a lentivirus vector that allowed for the cloning of genes for two chains of TCR.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Two of the research programs sparked gene therapy start-up companies, Calimmune and Immune Design Corp, founded in 2006 and 2008 respectively.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] A third program focused on the development of an HIV vaccine, and eventually lead to clinical trials at NIH.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2009 Baltimore became director of the Joint Center for Translational Medicine, a shared initiative between Caltech and UCLA aimed at developing bench to bedside medicine.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] A focus of Baltimore's lab from his arrival at Caltech to the lab's closure in 2018 was understanding the role of microRNA in the immune system.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] MicroRNAs provide fine control over gene expression by regulating the amount of protein made by particular messenger RNAs.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In recent research led by Jimmy Zhao, Baltimore's team has discovered a small RNA molecule called microRNA-146a (miR-146a) and bred a strain of mice that lacks miR146a.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] They have used the miR146a(-) mice as a model to study the effects of chronic inflammation on the activity of hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Their results suggest that microRNA-146a protects HSCs during chronic inflammation, and that its lack may contribute to blood cancers and bone marrow failure.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Another concentration within Baltimore's lab in recent years was control of inflammatory and immune responses, specifically splicing control of gene expression after inflammatory stimuli.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2013 they discovered that ordered expression of genes following an inflammatory stimulus was controlled by splicing, not transcription as previously supposed.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] This led to further discoveries that delayed splicing was caused by introns, with the revelation that RNA-binding protein BUD13 acts at this intron to increase the amount of successful splicing (2 articles by Luke Frankiw published in 2019 and 2020).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In an autobiographical piece published in Annual Review Immunology in 2019, Baltimore announced that half of his lab space at Caltech would be taken over by a new assistant professor in Fall 2018, and his current lab group would be the last.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In the span of his career, Baltimore profoundly influenced national science policy debates, including the AIDS epidemic and recombinant DNA research.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] His efforts to organize the Asilomar Conference on Recombinant DNA were key to creating consensus within scientific and policy spheres.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In recent years, Baltimore joined with other scientists to call for a worldwide moratorium on use of a new genome-editing technique to alter inheritable human DNA.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] A key step enabling researchers to slice up any DNA sequence they choose was developed by Emmanuelle Charpentier, then at Umea University in Sweden, and Jennifer A.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Doudna of the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Reminiscent of the Asilomar conference on recombinant DNA in 1975, those involved want both scientists and the public to be more aware of the ethical issues and risks involved with new techniques for genome modification.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] An early spokesperson for federal funding for AIDS research, Baltimore co-chaired the 1986 National Academy of Sciences committee on a National Strategy for AIDS.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Wolff were invited by the National Academy of Sciences and the Institute of Medicine to coauthor an independent report: *Confronting AIDS* (1986), in which they called for a $1 billion research program for HIV/AIDS.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] As of 1996 he was appointed head of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) AIDS Vaccine Research Committee (AVRC).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore held nearly 100 different biotechnology patents in the US and Europe, and had been preeminent in American biotechnology since the 1970s.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In addition to Calimmune and Immune Design, he also helped found s2A Molecular, Inc.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He consulted at various companies including Collaborative Research, Bristol Myers Squibb, and most recently Virtualitics.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He served on the board of directors at several companies and non-profit institutions including Regulus Therapeutics and Appia Bio.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was also a member of numerous Scientific Advisory Boards, and served with PACT Pharma, Volastra Therapeutics, Vir Biotechnology, and the Center for Infectious Diseases Research at Westlake University.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was the principal scientific advisor for the Science Philanthropy Alliance.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore's honors included the 1970 Gustave Stern Award in Virology, 1971 Eli Lilly and Co.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Award in Microbiology or Immunology, 1999 National Medal of Science, and 2000 Warren Alpert Foundation Prize.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was elected to the National Academy of Sciences USA (NAS) in1974; the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1974; the NAS Institute of Medicine (IOM), 1974; the American Association of Immunologists, 1984; the American Philosophical Society, 1997.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 1987; the French Academy of Sciences, 2000; and the American Association for Cancer Research (AACR).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He was also a member of the Pontifical Academy of Sciences, 1978.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2008, Baltimore was president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He published over 700 peer-reviewed articles.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore was a member of the USA Science and Engineering Festival's Advisory Board and an Xconomist (an editorial advisor for the tech news and media company, Xconomy).
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore also served on The Jackson Laboratory's board of trustees, the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists' Board of Sponsors, Amgen, Inc.'s board of directors, and numerous other organizations and their boards.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2019 Caltech named a graduate fellowship program in biochemistry and molecular biophysics in honor of Baltimore.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The program combined a $7.5 million gift from the Amgen Foundation with an existing one-year Amgen fellowship and $3.75 million given by Caltech's Gordon and Betty Moore Graduate Fellowship Match.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] During the late 1980s and early 1990s, Thereza Imanishi-Kari, a scientist who was in a separate, independent, laboratory at MIT but who had collaborated with Baltimore, was implicated in a case of scientific fraud.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The case received extensive news coverage and a Congressional investigation.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The case was linked to Baltimore's name because of his scientific collaboration with and later his strong defense of Imanishi-Kari against accusations of fraud.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1986, while a professor of biology at MIT and director at Whitehead, Baltimore co-authored a scientific paper on immunology with Thereza Imanishi-Kari (an assistant professor of biology who had her own laboratory at MIT) as well as four others.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] A postdoctoral fellow in Imanishi-Kari's laboratory, Margot O'Toole, who was not an author, reported concerns about the paper, ultimately accusing Imanishi-Kari of fabricating data in a cover-up.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore, however, refused to retract the paper.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] O'Toole soon dropped her challenge, but the NIH, which had funded the contested paper's research, began investigating, at the insistence of Walter W.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Stewart, a self-appointed fraud buster, and Ned Feder, his lab head at the NIH.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Representative John Dingell (D-MI) also aggressively pursued it, eventually calling in U.S.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Around October 1989, when Baltimore was appointed president of Rockefeller University, around a third of the faculty opposed his appointment because of concerns about his behaviour in the Imanishi-Kari case.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] He visited every laboratory, one by one, to hear those concerns directly from each group of researchers.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In a draft report dated March 14, 1991, based mainly on USSS forensics findings, NIH's fraud unit, then called the Office of Scientific Integrity (OSI), accused Imanishi-Kari of falsifying and fabricating data.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] It also criticized Baltimore for failing to embrace O'Toole's challenge.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Less than a week later, the report was leaked to the press.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore and three co-authors then retracted the paper; however, Imanishi-Kari and Moema H.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In the report, Baltimore stated that he may have been "too willing to accept" Imanishi-Kari's explanations and felt he "did too little to seek an independent verification of her data and conclusions." Baltimore publicly apologized for not taking a whistle-blower's charge more seriously.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Amid concerns raised by negative publicity in connection with the scandal, Baltimore resigned as president of Rockefeller University and rejoined the MIT Biology faculty.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In July 1992, the US Attorney for the District of Maryland, who had been investigating the case, announced he would not bring criminal or civil charges against Imanishi-Kari.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] An HHS appeals panel began meeting in June 1995 to review all charges in detail.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In June 1996, the panel ruled that the ORI had failed to prove any of its 19 charges.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] After throwing out much of the documentary evidence gathered by the ORI, the panel dismissed all charges against Imanishi-Kari.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Responsibility ... must be shared by all participants." Neither OSI nor ORI ever accused Baltimore of research misconduct.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The reputations of Stewart and Feder, who had pushed for the investigation, were badly damaged.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The pair were reassigned to other positions at NIH because they failed to maintain productivity in their roles as scientists and questions were raised about the legitimacy of their self-appointed inquiries into scientific integrity.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The Imanishi-Kari controversy was one among several prominent scientific integrity cases of the 1980s and 1990s in the United States.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In nearly all cases, defendants were ultimately cleared.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The case profoundly impacted the process for handling of scientific misconduct in the United States.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore has been both defended and criticized for his actions in this matter.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 1993, Yale University mathematician Serge Lang strongly criticized Baltimore's behavior.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Historian of science Daniel Kevles, writing after the exoneration of Imanishi-Kari, recounted the affair in his 1998 book, *The Baltimore Case*.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Horace Freeland Judson also gives a critical assessment of Baltimore's actions in *The Great Betrayal: Fraud In Science*.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In 2005, at Baltimore's request, Caltech began investigating the work that Luk van Parijs had conducted while a postdoc in Baltimore's laboratory.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Van Parijs first came under suspicion at MIT, for work done after he had left Baltimore's lab.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] After van Parijs had been fired by MIT, his doctoral supervisor also noted problems with work van Parijs did at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, before leaving Harvard to go to Baltimore's lab.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] The Caltech investigation concluded in March 2007.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] It found van Parijs alone committed research misconduct, and that four papers co-authored by Baltimore, van Parijs, and others required correction.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] In May 2021, Baltimore was quoted in the *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists* in an article about the origins of the COVID-19 virus, saying, "When I first saw the furin cleavage site in the viral sequence, with its arginine codons, I said to my wife it was the smoking gun for the origin of the virus.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] These features make a powerful challenge to the idea of a natural origin for SARS2." This quote was widely shared and gave credence to the possibility of a Wuhan lab leak that has been discussed extensively as part of investigations into the origin of COVID-19.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] A month later, Baltimore told the *Los Angeles Times* that he "should have softened the phrase 'smoking gun' because I don't believe that it proves the origin of the furin cleavage site but it does sound that way.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore died from cancer at his home in Woods Hole, Massachusetts, on September 6, 2025, at the age of 87.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Campbell (1978) General Virology 3rd edition John Wiley and Sons, New York, New York.
[src:david-baltimore/david-baltimore] Baltimore (1986) Molecular Cell Biology, Scientific American, New York, New York.
